OK, I&#39;ll revert to KR&#39;s letter names for now. But I promise to start
another thread on that subject before long.

I hadn&#39;t realized that you were linking these choices. Putting your
proposal in columns (this may require a monospace font to look OK):

Set       Choice 1     Choice 2
SQUARE    Et + Roe     Eight + Roe
NEAR      It + Roe     Eat + Roe
CURE      Foot + Roe   Ooze + Roe

I vote for Choice 1. After all, I&#39;m interested in reform--even in
reforming the reform alphabet! Even so, I&#39;m willing to submit to the
will of the majority on this one.

Now let&#39;s turn to NORTH and FORCE. According to the handout you cited,
&quot;In both standard accents, the FORCE words, historically distinct from
NORTH words, have now become or are now in the process of becoming
merged with them.&quot;

For the majority then, this would become an &#39;i before e&#39; type of rule:
For &#39;long O&#39;, use &#39;Owe&#39; except before &#39;Roe&#39;, in which case use &#39;Awe&#39;.
This feels unnatural to me.

On the other hand, what would be the cost of having the majority use
&#39;Owe&#39; + &#39;Roe&#39; for both NORTH and FORCE? Couldn&#39;t those who distinguish
the two still do so by using &#39;Owe&#39; and &#39;Awe&#39; as appropriate?

Ted


