&gt;
&gt;  As I said before, Et/Ate, It/Eat, and Foot/Ooze are neutralized before
&gt;  Roe, so one of the pair has to be chosen more or less at random.
&gt;  I would much prefer consistency (either Et, It, and Foot, or else Ate,
&gt;  Eat, and Ooze), and weakly favor the second set on historical grounds.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; 4) NORTH and FORCE: use &#39;Oak&#39; + &#39;Roar&#39;. (I am less open to persuasion.)
&gt;
&gt;  Here the trouble is that for *most* people this distinction (historically
&gt;  Awe/Owe) is also neutralized, but for dialects including Scottish, Irish,
&gt;  Eastern New England, and parts of the American South, these sounds are
&gt;  quite different: &quot;horse&quot; (NORTH) does not sound the same as &quot;hoarse&quot;
&gt;  (FORCE), nor is &quot;for&quot; (NORTH) like &quot;four&quot; (FORCE).
&gt;
&gt;  That being so, since the unmerged sound of NORTH is essentially THOUGHT
&gt;  + /r/, whereas FORCE is essentially GOAT + /r/, I&#39;d prefer to reserve
&gt;  Owe-Roe for people who need a separate spelling for FORCE, and the rest
&gt;  of us use Awe-Roe for both NORTH and FORCE. Note that people who merge
&gt;  PALM and THOUGHT still retain a Awe-type vowel before /r/; that is,
&gt;  they do not merge NORTH/FORCE with START.
&gt;
&gt;  (Second rant: FORCE is another sucky name, because &quot;north&quot; and &quot;force&quot;
&gt;  both use the &quot;or&quot; spelling, making it unnecessarily hard to remember which
&gt;  is which: COARSE would have been better. But standards are standards.)
